Title: "El Güero Polkas"
Description: A classic example of conjunto music, a regional genre born of cross-cultural exchanges between Europeans and Mexicans which thrived in South and Central Texas, exhibits strong influences from the German polka and accordion. The bajo-sexto, a lower sizth-bass guitar that is native to Mexico, reflects the Mecican influiences in this musical style. This song, along with many others, was recorded in San Antonio between 1955 and 1967.

Title: "Talk to Me"
Description: One of the most well-known songs within San Antono-born "Westside Sound" genre, "Talk to Me" is an example of intercultural music, fusing elements of elements of rock-and-roll, rhythm-and-blues, soul, etc.

Title: "Abre Los Ojos"
Description: Performed and recorded between 1951 and 1963 by the "Texas Conjunto Pioneer", Valerio Longoria, this Ranchera reflects Mexican influences on popular South and Central Texas music of the time.

Title: "A Blossom Fell"
Description: Nat King Cole's single debuted at #1 on the U.S. Pop Charts in 1955, the same year he and Duke Ellington made appearances at San Antonio's Majestic Theatre and Keyhole Club to promote their project, ''Rock N' Roll Revue''.

Title: "She's About A Mover"
Description: Based in San Antonio, bandmates Doug Sahm, Augie Meyers, Frank Morin, Jack Barber, and Johnny Perez hopped on the "British Invasion" craze of the 1960s with this hit.

Title: "Oh Please Love Me"
Description: A popular doo-wap ballad by San Antonio group, The Lyrics, charted at #14 on local KONO radio in September 1959. This song, and others by the group and Harlem label, showcase the influence of doo-wap and R&B in the city during this time.
